1 Goal of the EDA:

The goal of this EDA is to understand how effective in-store promos and ads are for General Mills products. This will help assess whether expenses on marketing efforts are yielding the required return.

  • Load raw data
  • Make changes to data based on business rules definitions
  • Perform joins as required
raw_data_product <- read_csv("mtp_product_data.csv")
raw_data_sales <- read_csv("mtp_sales_data.csv")

# separating producer and product name, because product name is combination of both

product <- raw_data_product %>% 
  mutate(UPC = str_replace_all(str_sub(UPC, 4), "-", ""),
         brand_name = case_when(
           str_detect(brand, "GENERAL MILLS") ~ "General Mills",
           str_detect(brand, "KELLOGGS") ~ "Kelloggs",
           str_detect(brand, "POST") ~ "Post"),
         product_name = str_trim(
           str_to_title(
             str_replace(brand, toupper(brand_name), ""), "left")),
         flavor = str_to_title(flavor),
         package = str_to_title(package))

# defining columns based on whether promo, discounts and ads are run, for easier labeling in plots

sales <- raw_data_sales %>% 
  mutate(UPC = str_replace_all(UPC, "\\.", ""),
         discount_offered = if_else(promo == 1, "Yes", "No"),
         promo = if_else(promo == 1, "With Promo", "Without Promo"),
         ad = case_when(ad == "A" ~ "Large",
                        ad == "B"~ "Medium or Small",
                        TRUE ~ "None"),
         promo_plus_ad = case_when(
           promo == "With Promo" & ad == "None" ~ "Promo",
           promo == "Without Promo" & ad != "None" ~ "Ad",
           promo != "Without Promo" & ad != "None" ~ "Both",
           TRUE ~ "None"
         ),
         sales = round(price * units, 2),
         quarter_nbr = ceiling(4 * week / 52)
         )

# joining the data

cereal <- left_join(product, sales) %>% 
  rename(upc = UPC, store_nbr = iri_key, week_nbr = week) %>% 
  mutate(upc = factor(upc),
         store_nbr = factor(store_nbr),
         brand_name = factor(brand_name),
         product_name = factor(product_name),
         flavor = factor(flavor),
         package = factor(package),
         discount_offered = factor(discount_offered),
         promo = factor(promo),
         ad = factor(ad),
         promo_plus_ad = factor(promo_plus_ad),
         week_nbr = factor(week_nbr),
         quarter_nbr = factor(quarter_nbr)
         ) %>% 
  select(upc, brand_name, product_name, flavor, store_nbr, 
         units, price, sales,
         everything()) %>% 
  select(-brand)

  • Data is provided for 52 weeks
  • There are 15 different types of cereal that are being sold
    • Raw data shows 114 different items
    • This means each product sells at multiple levels of volume, or
    • Each product may sell by more than one type of packaging or flavor
  • There are a few unusually large purchases
    • We know this as units is right skewed
  • There are a few products selling at very low prices.
    • We need to confirm what those are.
    • We know this as price is left skewed
  • As expected, majority of sales are done without promos or ads
    • Promos and ads are run together about 6.5% of the time

8 ## Univariate graphical – Quantitative

We need to look at histograms of quantitative variables to confirm what we have just seen.

# Code histograms using grid.arrange so can see all quant variables together
# histogram to see how sales, price, unit and volume is distributed in sample given
grid.arrange(
  cereal %>% 
    ggplot(aes(units)) +
      geom_histogram() +
       theme_minimal() +
    theme(
      panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
      panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    axis.line = element_line(colour = "#D3D3D3")),
  cereal %>% 
    ggplot(aes(price)) +
      geom_histogram() +
       theme_minimal() +
    theme(
      panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
      panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    axis.line = element_line(colour = "#D3D3D3")),
  cereal %>% 
    ggplot(aes(sales)) +
      geom_histogram() +
       theme_minimal() +
    theme(
      panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
      panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    axis.line = element_line(colour = "#D3D3D3")),
  cereal %>% 
    ggplot(aes(volume)) +
      geom_histogram() +
       theme_minimal() +
    theme(
      panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
      panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    axis.line = element_line(colour = "#D3D3D3")),
  ncol = 2
)

Conclusions:

  • Number of Units sold has a skewed distribution
    • It makes sense because normally people don’t buy in large quantities
  • Price of the product is almost normally distributed but interesting variable will be price per unit
  • Sales distribution is almost similar to units sold
    • It makes sense because they can be highly correlated
  • Volume of each package shows that most demand is around unit 1.0
    • But there are still outliers at both extremes

14.3.2 Does cereal popularity differ across stores?

Following is the method used:

  • Products are ranked by store
  • The ranked products are placed into 3 tiers:
    • The top 33% of ranks are placed into the “Top Third”
    • The middle 33% of ranks are placed into the “Middle Third”
    • The bottom 33% of ranks are placed into the “Bottom Third”
  • Note: Not every product sells in every store, per the sample. Hence the division into three tiers accordingly.
    • If 12 cereals sell in a store, Ranks 1-4, 5-8, 9-12 are placed into the tiers respectively.

Interpretation of graph below: For every product, in how many stores is it present in the “Top Third”, “Middle Third” and “Bottom Third”.

# mapping of brands, products and flavors

brand_product_mapping <- cereal %>% 
  select(brand_name, product_name, flavor) %>% 
  filter(!(product_name == "Lucky Charms" & flavor == "Regular" |
             product_name == "Cheerios" & flavor == "Regular")) %>% 
  unique()

# ranking cereal into tiers by week, quarter and overall

cereal_rank_tiers <- cereal %>% 
  group_by(store_nbr, product_name) %>% 
  summarise(total_revenue = sum(sales)) %>% 
  mutate(cereal_rank = dense_rank(desc(total_revenue))) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  group_by(store_nbr) %>% 
  mutate(cereal_rank_bin = case_when(
    cereal_rank <= 1 * ceiling(n() / 3) ~ "Top Third",
    cereal_rank <= 2 * ceiling(n() / 3) ~ "Middle Third",
    cereal_rank <= 3 * ceiling(n() / 3) ~ "Lower Third"
  )) %>% 
  select(-total_revenue) %>% 
  group_by(product_name, cereal_rank_bin) %>% 
  summarise(no_of_stores = n()) %>% 
  inner_join(brand_product_mapping) %>% 
  select(brand_name, flavor, everything())

most_popular_cereal_gm <- most_popular_cereal %>% 
  ungroup() %>% filter(brand_name == "General Mills") %>% as.data.frame()
gen_mills_ranked <- as.character(most_popular_cereal_gm$product_name)
ranking_tiers <- c("Top Third", "Middle Third", "Lower Third")

# Bar chart showing popularity by product, color fade, **GM only**

ggplot(data = cereal_rank_tiers %>% 
         filter(brand_name == "General Mills"), 
       aes(x = factor(product_name, levels = rev(gen_mills_ranked)), 
           y = no_of_stores, 
           fill = cereal_rank_bin
             # factor(cereal_rank_bin, levels = rev(ranking_tiers))
           )
  ) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  scale_x_discrete(
    name = element_blank(), expand = c(0, 0)
  ) + 
  scale_y_continuous(
    name = "Number of stores", expand = c(0, 0)
  ) +
  scale_fill_manual(name = "Cereal Rank Tier", 
                    values = c(colour_red_1, colour_yellow_1, colour_green_2)) +
  guides(fill = guide_legend(reverse = TRUE)) +
  theme_minimal() + 
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(colour = "black", face = "bold", size = 13),
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    axis.line = element_line(colour = colour_grey_3)
  ) +
  ggtitle(
    label = "Top performing cereals overall are popular across all stores", 
    subtitle = "Cheerios is the top performing product but does not sell everywhere"
  ) +
  coord_flip()

Conclusions:

  • Cheerios is our top performing product but sells in only 850 stores.
    • That seems unexpected
  • Top performers are generally in the Top Third in more stores than others.
    • This is expected, but it’s good to have confirmation.

cereal_price_comp <- cereal %>% 
  filter(!(product_name == "Lucky Charms" & flavor == "Regular" |
             product_name == "Cheerios" & flavor == "Regular"))

# boxplot showing price ranges

price_boxplot <- function(packaging = "Box") {
  ggplot(
    data = cereal_price_comp %>% filter(brand_name != "Post", package == packaging), 
    aes(x = reorder(product_name, sales, sum), 
        y = price, 
        fill = brand_name)
  ) +
    geom_boxplot() +
    facet_grid(
      factor(flavor, 
             levels = c("Regular", "Toasted", "Cinnamon Toast", "Fruit", "Cocoa")
      ) ~ .,
      space = "free_y", scales = "free_y"
    ) +
    scale_fill_manual(
      name = "Producer",
      values = c(colour_red_1, colour_grey_3)
    ) +
    theme_light() +
    theme(
      plot.title = element_text(colour = "black", face = "bold", size = 13),
      panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
      panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
      axis.title.y = element_blank(),
      legend.position = "bottom",
      strip.background = element_rect(fill = colour_grey_1, colour = "grey"),
      strip.text.y = element_text(
        colour = "black", size = 11, face = "bold",
        angle = 360
      )
    ) +
    coord_flip() +
    ggtitle(
      label = "Prices similar to main competition",
      subtitle = "Cheerios is priced at a lower level vs competition"
    )
}

price_boxplot(packaging = "Box")

Conclusions:

  • Our prices are similar to competition
  • Cheerios is priced on the lower side
    • This may mean we don’t have as much room for discouting
  • Outliers on either side is indication of wide choice available
  • Very low prices may indicate large discounts too; need to investigate further

A summary of price information may confirm what we have seen above.

    skim(price) %>%

}

14.6 Are promos effective?

14.6.1 How do stores that run promos fare in general?

brand_focus <- "General Mills"

# sales and units by product, separated by promo v/s no promo

prod_rev_promo <- cereal %>%
  filter(brand_name == brand_focus) %>%
  group_by(product_name, store_nbr, promo) %>%
  summarise(avg_revenue = mean(sales), avg_units = mean(units))

# sales and units by product
# separated by stores that ran promos v/s those that never ran promos during the year

promo_store_with_out_comp <- prod_rev_promo %>%
  mutate(store_both_with_out = if_else(
    sum(promo == "With Promo") + sum(promo == "Without Promo") == 2,
    "Ran Promo", "No Promo")) %>%
  group_by(product_name, store_both_with_out) %>%
  summarise(avg_rev_per_store = mean(avg_revenue),
            avg_qty_per_store = mean(avg_units))

# plot showing average sales between stores that ran promos v/s others

ggplot(
    data = promo_store_with_out_comp,
    aes(x = factor(product_name, levels = rev(gen_mills_ranked)),
        y = avg_rev_per_store, fill = store_both_with_out)
  ) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_x_discrete(name = element_blank()) +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Average units sold per store per week") +

    name = element_blank(),

    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    axis.line = element_line(colour = colour_grey_3)
  ) +
  ggtitle(label = "Stores that ran promos had lower average sales",
          subtitle = "Cinnamon Toast Crunch is the only exception") +
  labs(
    caption = "Note: Stores that ran promos are compared to stores that did not run promos at all during the year"
  ) +
  coord_flip()

Conclusions:

  • Stores that ran promos had lower average sales for each product
  • This makes sense as promos may be run to boost sales

14.6.2 How is product performance affected by in-store promos?

Note: Promos involve a discount of at least 5%. Hence, in order for promos to be effective, there needs to be an increase in quantity sold of at least 5.3% (approx, calculated) just to break even.

Since promos are running in-store, we need to compare product performance within a store with v/s without promo in order to truly know how effective they are.

# average revenue per store per week, with promo v/s without
# this only considers stores where data shows sales with AND without promo
# this is because raw data is a sample of sales

promo_comp_gm <- prod_rev_promo %>% 
  mutate(store_both_with_out = 
           sum(promo == "With Promo") + sum(promo == "Without Promo")) %>% 
  filter(store_both_with_out == 2) %>% 
  select(-store_both_with_out) %>% 
  group_by(product_name, promo) %>% 
  summarise(avg_rev_per_store = mean(avg_revenue),
            avg_qty_per_store = mean(avg_units))

# bar plot showing average sales per store with and without promo

ggplot(
    data = promo_comp_gm, 
    aes(x = factor(product_name, levels = rev(gen_mills_ranked)), 
        y = avg_rev_per_store,

  ) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  theme_minimal() +

Conclusions:

  • All products made more money on average per week per store when promos were run
    • The exception is Cheerios
  • This might mean one of two things:
    • Discounts were high (we don’t know the actual level of discount)
    • Demand didn’t increase by a larger percentage than the discount offered
# T-TESTS

# we are comparing average revenue and units with and without promo
# like previous, we are only considering stores with data on both sales with and without promo

t_test_data_promo <- prod_rev_promo %>% 
  inner_join(
    prod_rev_promo %>% mutate(
      store_both_with_out = sum(promo == "With Promo") + sum(promo == "Without Promo")
    ) %>% 
      filter(store_both_with_out == 2)
    ) %>% 
  select(-store_both_with_out) %>% 
  group_by(product_name, store_nbr, promo) %>%
  summarise(avg_rev_per_store = mean(avg_revenue),
            avg_qty_per_store = mean(avg_units))
  
t_test_data_sls_promo <- t_test_data_promo %>% select(-avg_qty_per_store) %>% 
  spread(promo, avg_rev_per_store) %>%
  rename(`Ran Promo` = `With Promo`, `No Promo` = `Without Promo`)
t_test_data_qty_promo <- t_test_data_promo %>% select(-avg_rev_per_store) %>% 
  spread(promo, avg_qty_per_store) %>%
  rename(`Ran Promo` = `With Promo`, `No Promo` = `Without Promo`)

14.8.1 Do our findings have statistical validity?

Following points are important in our estimation of models:

  • Models are run on log sales as sales does not follow a normal distribution
  • We have included the following variables as they are the main questions of interest that can be influenced by General Mills:
    • promo: implying if a sale has included an promo
    • ad: implying if a sale has included an ad
    • promo * ad: this interaction term tells us if a promo and ad was run together.
  • The following variables have not been included:
    • package: a product cannot change its packaging easily
    • flavor: a product cannot change its flavor easily
    • volume: a product cannot change its volume easily
    • brand_name: we are running separate models for every product, limited to General Mills
    • units: jointly determined with revenue
    • price: jointly determined with revenue
  • Data includes all stores
  • Models are being run separately for revenue and units
    • This is to assess the impact of promos and/or ads on both variables
  • Our hypotheses:
    • Running promos or ads helps increase demand (by way of units sold), with promos and ads together being more effective.
    • But, promos, esp are affecting margins due to the discounts included.
# MODELING

model_data <- cereal %>%
  select(brand_name, product_name, store_nbr, sales, units, promo, ad) %>% 
  # inner_join(prod_rev_promo %>% select(product_name, store_nbr) %>% unique(), 
  #            by = c("product_name", "store_nbr")) %>% 
  mutate(ad = if_else(ad == "None", "Without Ad", "With Ad")) %>% 
  mutate(ad = factor(ad, levels = c("Without Ad", "With Ad"))) %>% 
  select(-store_nbr)

model_data$promo <- relevel(model_data$promo, ref = "Without Promo")
model_data$ad <- relevel(model_data$ad, ref = "Without Ad")

model_data_gm_sls <- model_data %>% 
  filter(brand_name == "General Mills") %>%
  select(-brand_name, -units)
model_data_gm_qty <- model_data %>% 
  filter(brand_name == "General Mills") %>%
  select(-brand_name, -sales)

# CONSTRUCT SALES MODELS

sales_model_gm_cheerios <- lm(data = model_data_gm_sls %>% 
        filter(product_name == "Cheerios") %>% select(-product_name), 
        log(sales) ~ . + promo * ad)

Conclusions:

  • Promos are shown to be effective for increasing quantity demanded as well as revenue.
  • Promos plus ads together aren’t quite as effective.
  • Ads are shown to have a negative impact, but since the respective variables are not statistically significant, we don’t have enough evidence to make the conclusion.

15 What we have learned

  • Both promos and ads are effective in increasing demand (in terms of units)
    • Promos and ads together are even more effective
  • For most products, revenue is either at similar levels or higher when promos and/or ads are run
  • Cheerios is the exception
    • Cheerios is priced at a lower level
    • Hence, discounts offered through promos are cutting into margins
    • We don’t know how large discounts were, so they may have been larger than 5%

Key takeaway: Promos and ads are effective in driving demand for all products, but it may be cutting margins for Cheerios, which is priced lower and is the top seller, due to discounts offered, while having a limited impact on revenue for other products. Hence, it may be prudent to review how much discount is being offered via promos, esp for Cheerios.
